Wagner continued his LB1 run against the Ravens, tallying six solos and six assists. The LB5 on the season, Wagner has recorded five or more solos in five of six games this season and had 1.5 sacks in the one game he failed to hit that mark.

Spillane was solid in Week 6, racking up five solos, three assists, and one pass defended. This was the first time all season Spillane failed to record six or more solos and just the second time all season that he failed to register at least seven. Spillane is a top-three LB option until he cools down. Treat him as such for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Wilson was solid in Week 6, racking up five solos and four assists. Logan has been one of the most consistent in the league, registering five or more solos in each of his six games this season. Tap Wilson as an LB1 option for a tasty Week 7 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Zaire did Zaire things in Week 6, amassing eight solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. He has recorded five or more solos in four of his last five games and should continue to be counted on as an LB1 option for Week 7 against the Miami Dolphins.

Lavonte lit up the stat sheet again in Week 6, this time recording six solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Lavonte has been producing at an LB1 level and shows no signs of slowing down. Continue to treat him as an LB1 option for a tasty Week 7 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Pratt was at it again in Week 6, racking up five solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Pratt has recorded five or more solos in each of his last five games and has been contributing in the ancillary stats. Fire him up as an LB1 option until he cools off.

Dodson was solid in Week 6, notching five solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Dodson has been inconsistent in the solo department this season but has been busy enough in the peripherals to make him the LB10 on the season. Dodson has added two sacks, five tackles for loss, one forced fumble, one fumble recovery, and two passes defended through six games. Start Dodson as an LB1 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Quay went off in Week 6, exploding for 10 solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. Quay has registered six or more solos in five of his six games this season and should be considered a top-15 option going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Houston Texans.

JOK went off in Week 6, racking up four solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He has been shining as a starter this season and has produced his way into the top-15 conversation due to a steady stream of tackles combined with work in the peripheral stats. Treat him as an elite LB2 for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Watt was excellent in Week 6, racking up five solos, two tackles for loss, and two forced fumbles. Watt has 4.5 sacks on the season, but as games like Week 6 prove, he can be a force even when not taking down the quarterback. Watt has 12 solos and three forced fumbles in his past two games alone. Continue to treat Watt as a top-three DL option and an IDP1.

Lloyd was solid in Week 6, tallying four solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Lloyd has been inconsistent since getting hurt, but this was a step in the right direction. Unfortunately, it looks like Ventrell Miller can soak up tackles at a high rate, so Lloyd remains an LB3 at best. Tap him as a LB3/4 for Week 7.

Wallace impressed again in Week 6, racing up six solos, three assists, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Wallace has been excellent since moving into the starting lineup for the injured Shaq Thompson and should be considerred a LB2 play the rest of the way. He has recorded 16 solos over his last two games and projects as an impact producer going forward. Fire Wallace up as a top-20 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against Jayden Daniels and Washington. Add Wallace in all formats.

Queen was excellent in Week 6, reeling off six solos, seven assists, and one tackle for loss. Queen has now put together back-to-back outings with six solos, putting him back in the LB3 mix. It's obvious that he won't match his production from last season, but he can still provide value, especially during the byes. Tap Queen as an LB3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the New York Jets.

Murray was at it again in Week 6, racking up six solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Murray has reeled off five or more solos in each of his last four games and has cemented himself as a LB2 play going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.
Ivan Pace racked up five solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Pace is a borderline LB2 for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Detroit Lions. Start him where needed.

Sherwood surprised in Week 6, racking up seven solos and six assists. He remained productive even with C.J. Mosley returning to the lineup, as the veteran played limited snaps. As productive as Sherwood was with Mosley sidelined, Mosley is going to return to an everydown role once he is ready. Leave Sherwood on benches for Week 7.

Nakobe was excellent in Week 6, racking up seven solos and five assists. Nakobe has quietly tallied five or more solos in three of his five games this season and has been a solid LB3. He has failed to live up to the lofty expectations thrust upon him when he beat out Devin White but is start worthy in all leagues that can start three or more LBs. Tap Nakobe as a top-25 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

McFadden continued to impress in Week 6, notching three solos, two assists, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery.  Fire him up as an LB3 with LB2 upside for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Strnad was excellent in Week 6, racking up five solos, two assists, and one sack. Strnad has five or more solos in each of his last two games and has two sacks in his last three games. He has been filling in admirably for Alex Singleton and will continue to start for the rest of the season based on his performances. Start Strnad with confidence as an LB2/3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the New Orleans Saints. Add Strnad in all competitive leagues.

Deablo stepped up in Week 6, racking up three solos, three assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Deablo was excellent in his first game back from the oblique injury and should continue to thrive beside Robert Spillane. Spillane soaks up enough tackles to keep Deablo as more of an LB3 than an LB2, but games like this serve to highlight Divine's true upside. Add and start Deablo as an LB3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Landman was excellent in Week 7, tallying four solos, four assists, and two forced fumbles. Landman had been sidelined since Week 1, and Hasan expanded role for as long as Troy Andersen remains sidelined. Fire Landman up if Andersen misses more time. If Andersen returns, Landman can be left on benches.

Hewitt flashed in Week 6, registering six solos and three assists against the New England Patriots. Hewitt saw an expanded role due to Azeez Al-Shaair being injured and should start this week if Azeez remains sidelined. Treat Hewitt as an LB4/flex for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Ventrell Miller stayed productive in Week 6, racking up eight solos, two assists, and one forced fumble. He has recorded six or more solos in three straight games and can be counted as an LB2 option until he cools down. Ventrell should be rostered in all competitive leagues, especially during the byes. Tap Miller as a top-25 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the New England Patriots. Add Miller wherever available.

Cooper was solid in Week 6, tallying six solos and two assists. Cooper has been inconsistent this season and should not be plugged into lineups on a light bye. He has considerable upside and should remain rostered in deeper leagues, but leave him on the pine for Week 7 despite the plus matchup against the Houston Texans.

Krys was excellent in Week 6, racking up eight solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. He saw an expanded role against the Packers due to the injury to Kyzir White and will continue to soak up snaps in White misses any time. Barnes is a speculative add but will be drop worthy if White returns for Week 7, so plan your FAAB budget accordingly. With that said, Barnes has LB3 upside if Kyzir is sidelined, so he is someone for deep leaguers to stash while we wait for an update on Kyzir. Add Barnes where needed.

Landry was a busy man in Week 6, notching five solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss against the Indianapolis Colts. Landry has four sacks on the season but if he can stay active in the solo department even when he is not getting sacks, he can quickly ascend to DL1 territory. For now, treat him as a DL2/3 for a plus Week 7 matchup against the new look Buffalo Bills.

Willie Gay was showed up in Week 6, racking up three solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Gay has failed to impress this season and could be in danger of losing snaps as the season progresses. Keep him out of lineups for Week 7, despite the plus matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Azeez took full advantage of the extra snaps in Week 6, menacing the Bengals for two solos, two assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Azeez should continue to be the main beneficiary of the absence of Kayvon Thibodeaux. Tap Ojulari as a DL3/4 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles. Add Ojulari where possible.

Love continued to shine in Week 6, racking up seven solos, three assists, and one pass defended. Love is locked in as a DB1 and seems to have captured the consistency that has eluded him in prior seasons. Tap him as a top-10 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Winfield was excellent in Week 6, tallying four solos, one pass defended, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. Winfield is a top-three option whenever he is on the field. Treat him as such for an exciting Week 7 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Jones was excellent in Week 6, going off for 11 solos, one assist, and one pass defended. Jones has been inconsistent all season but has another plus matchup on tap for Week 7, which puts him in the DB3 for those dealing with injuries or bye weeks. Jones has six or more total tackles in five of his six contests this year and will jump to DB2 territory in fantasy points per game after this outing. Tap Jones as a DB3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the New Orleans Saints. Add and start Jones where needed.

Nubin was excellent in Week 6, racking up five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Nubin has forced his way into the DB2 conversation over his last three games and has now recorded five or more solos in four of his six games this season, including three straight. Tap Nubin as a top-25 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Cam Bynum was excellent in Week 5, tallying four solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Bynum regained his DB1 form after a slow start to the season and can be counted as a top-12 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Woods showed up in Week 6, tallying seven solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Woods has picked it up lately, recording five or more solos in each of his last three games. He has four games with five or more solos on the season. Treat Woods as a top-25 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against Washington.

Moehrig was excellent in Week 6, racking up seven solos, two assists, and three tackles for loss. This was his most productive IDP outing of the season and keeps him in the DB3 mix for Week 7. Treat him as such for a neutral at best Week 7 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Harrison was excellent in Week 5, racking up five solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Harrison has been inconsistent this season, but spike games like this keep him in the DB2 discussion. Treat him as such for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Detroit Lions. Start Smith everywhere as a DB2.
Tyrann is active for Thursday Night Football and can be counted as a DB1 option, thanks to the plus matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Chinn was excellent in Week 6, reeling off seven solos and one assist against the Baltimore Ravens. Chinn has upped his production recently, registering seven or more solos in two of his last three games. He has started and played over 80 percent of the snaps in each of the games this season and finally seems to be regaining the form that made him a DB1 mainstay before things went haywire in Carolina. Tap Chinn as a top-25 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Hooker was excellent in Week 6, reeling off four solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Hooker has been inconsistent this season, but that is about what we expected. He has topped five solos just once all season and has hit four just twice. Treat him as more of a DB4/flex than a DB3. Those in leagues where you are required to start three or fewer DBs should league him on benches for a neutral at best Week 7 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Rapp was excellent in Week 6, racking up five solos, three assists, and three passes defended. Rapp has dealt with consistency issues all season as far as solos are concerned, and this was his first game above four solos. Outings like this serve to accentuate the upside IDP managers keep chasing, but Rapp is going to be hard to trust outside of heavy byes until he starts showing said consistency. Treat him as more of a DB4 than a DB3 for Week 7.

Tykee was at it again in Week 6, racking up three solos, two assists, one forced fumble, one interception, and two passes defended. Tykee has been a force out of the slot this season and is locked in as a CB1/DB3. He is going to have peaks and valleys, but so far, it has mostly been peaks. Fire him up as a CB1/DB3 despite the neutral at best Week 7 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Gilman showed up in Week 6, notching sic solos, four assists, one sack, and one pass defended. It was his first time above four solos all season, but is an encouraging sign for someone many still have rostered as a DB3 option, Gilman has proven DB2 upside and should be rostered in competitive leagues now that he has shown a flash of still being the players IDP managers have been waiting for. Tap Gilman as a DB3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Murray showed up in Week 6, tallying four solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Murray has been solid filling in for the injured Jimmie Ward and is slated to get another start this week against the Green Bay Packers. Treat Murray as a DB3/4 for the plus matchup.

Maye was excellent in Week 5, racking up five solos, four assists, and one pass defended. He drew the start with Jordan Poyer sidelined and is likely to draw at least a couple more, with Jevon Holland expected to be sidelined for at least a couple of weeks after suffering a broken bone in his hand against the New England Patriots. Maye makes for an intriguing DB3 play for as long as he is drawing starts for the Dolphins. Maye should be added in all competitive leagues.
Howden saw an expanded role in Week 6 due to Will Harris being sent to IR and responded with three solos and eight assists. Tap him as a DB2/3 for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Elijah Molden was excellent in Week 4, racking up five solos, three assists, and one fumble recovery. Molden is a solid option for CB leagues but should not be on radars in DB leagues until he shows some consistency. Look elsewhere for your Week 6 DB3.

McLeod was excellent in Week 6, tallying eight solos, one pass defended, and a touchdown. The special teams' touchdown is not something to chase, but the eight solos to follow up a six solo outing in Week 5 is. McLeod is a must-start DB3 option if Grant Delpit misses any more time. Make the speculative add just in case as Delpit missed practice all of last week while in concussion protocol.
